That is, he put himself under a vow. ‘⁶ This vow‚” saith Salmasius, “cannot be meant for a religious vow, be- cause the devoted hair was to be laid aside at Jerusalem, and to be put under the sacrifice of the peace-offering, It seems that it was a civil vow, that either Paul or Aquila took, such as the Jews did many times like it. ‘I will not shave my hair before I come to that place,’ which were the pilgrims' vows. So Paul made a vow to cut his hair when he came to Cenchrea. Of this kind were the vows or curses which they took upon themselves, not to take meat nor drink unless they did such a thing. As they who bound them- selves under a curse neither to eat nor drink until they had killed Paul, Acts xxiii. 12.” Yet there are many who understand this of the holy vow of the Nazarites, by which some bound themselves for a certain time, as others did for ever. For so long as they were bound by this vow, it was a heinous crime to shave their hair. See N umb. vi. 5.
